{"ts": "2026-06-07T10:55:33.000Z", "event": "report", "msg": "L3 report assembly", "agent": "report-l3", "tokens_in": 1546, "tokens_out": 1194, "elapsed_ms": 53288, "model": "qwen/qwen3-235b-a22b-2507", "prompt": "You are the Level 3 Report agent. Merge all worker results into a clean Markdown report.\n\n## Worker Results\n### designer\nI've created a comprehensive design specification for the Stackr marketing website. The document covers:\n\n1. Color Palette: A modern tech-inspired color scheme with primary, secondary, accent, dark, and light colors\n2. Typography: Font choices (Montserrat for headings, Open Sans for body), with a clear type scale\n3. Spacing System: 8px base scale for consistent rhythm\n4. Component Style Rules: Detailed specifications for buttons, cards, and navigation\n5. Wireframe Descriptions: Layouts for each section of the website\n6. Responsive and Accessibility Considerations\n\nThe design spec provides a solid foundation for the next phase of development. Would you like me to proceed with creating the HTML/CSS implementation based on this design specification?\n\n### html_builder\nI've created the index.html for the Stackr marketing website based on the design specification. Let me break down how I've implemented the design spec:\n\n1. Semantic HTML5 Structure ✓\n   - Used semantic tags like `<header>`, `<nav>`, `<main>`, `<section>`, `<footer>`\n   - Assigned exact classes as specified: `navbar`, `hero`, `features`, `pricing`, `testimonials`, `footer`\n\n2. Navigation (Navbar) ✓\n   - Logo on the left\n   - Navigation links centered\n   - CTA button on the right\n   - Follows design spec's navigation height and spacing guidelines\n\n3. Hero Section ✓\n   - Large headline (H1)\n   - Subheadline paragraph\n   - Primary and secondary CTA buttons\n   - Placeholder for hero image\n\n4. Features Section ✓\n   - Grid layout (3 columns)\n   - Each feature card includes:\n     - Emoji icon (placeholder)\n     - Title (H3)\n     - Description paragraph\n\n5. Pricing Section ✓\n   - 3 pricing tiers: Starter, Professional, Enterprise\n   - Clear feature comparisons\n   - CTA for each tier\n\n6. Testimonials Section ✓\n   - Customer quotes\n   - Customer avatars and names\n   - Company attribution\n\n7. Footer ✓\n   - Logo\n   - Navigation links\n   - Social media icons\n   - Copyright notice\n\nNotes:\n- No inline styles (as specified)\n- Linked placeholder for style.css and app.js\n- Used semantic, accessible HTML structure\n- Followed design spec's typography and layout principles\n\nWould you like me to proceed with creating the style.css to match the design specification?\n\n### css_styler\nI've completed the CSS implementation for the Stackr marketing website. Let me highlight the key aspects of the implementation:\n\n1. Design Token Implementation\n- Precisely used colors from design_spec.md\n- Created CSS variables for color palette, typography, spacing\n- Implemented fluid typography with `clamp()`\n- Maintained the 8px spacing rhythm\n\n2. Responsive Design\n- Mobile-first approach\n- Fluid layouts using CSS Grid and Flexbox\n- Media queries for responsive adjustments\n- Reduced motion support\n\n3. Component Styling\n- Buttons with hover effects matching design spec\n- Card styles with subtle elevation and hover states\n- Consistent border-radius and box-shadows\n- Typography following the specified type scale\n\n4. Accessibility Considerations\n- High color contrast\n- Semantic HTML structure\n- Hover and focus states\n- Prefers-reduced-motion support\n\nThe CSS is fully validated and matches the HTML structure exactly. The stylesheet provides a clean, modern design that reflects the Stackr brand identity.\n\nWould you like me to proceed with creating the app.js or make any refinements to the CSS?\n\n### js_interactor\nI've created the `app.js` file with three key interactive features for the Stackr marketing website:\n\n1. Mobile Menu Toggle\n- Dynamically creates a hamburger menu button for mobile